operly analyze the arguments in defense of criminal punishment. Second, the book argues that when such research is properly accounted for, none of the current attempts to justify criminal punishment succeed. But that does not imply that the state should do nothing about criminal wrongdoing. Rather, the arguments that were supposed to justify criminal punishment actually speak in favor of an alternative approach to criminal law: restitution to the victim and restorative justice. That is to say, the state should coerce offenders to provide restitution for the harm inflicted on victims, and whenever possible restorative approaches should be taken to address criminal wrongdoing.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aCriminal justice, Administration ofxPhilosophy. 0aCriminal lawxPhilosophy. 0aPrison abolition movements. 0aPunishmentxPhilosophy. 4aEntschädigung. 4aUngerechtigkeit. 4aVerbrechen. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  acompensation.  acrime.  awrongdoing.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2023z9783111318646oZDB-23-DPH0 cEPUBz97831110280260 cprintz978311102775340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311102782140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783111027821423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783111027821/original  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DGGb2023  aZDB-23-DPHb2023